body:
Using 12.0 (devel) on Windows, the following code 

```systemverilog
module AssignLiterals;
    initial begin
        string s;

        s = "A\0B";
        $display("1. '%s' len=%1d",s,s.len());

        s = "A\015\12B";
        $display("2. '%s' len=%1d",s,s.len());

        s = {"A","\015","\012","B"};
        $display("3. '%s' len=%1d",s,s.len());

        s = "A\170\171B";
        $display("4. '%s' len=%1d",s,s.len());

        s = {"A",8'o15,8'o12,"\012","B"};
        $display("5. '%s' len=%1d",s,s.len());
    end
endmodule
```
results in
```
1. 'A\000B' len=6
2. 'A\015\012B' len=10
3. 'A\015\012B' len=10
4. 'AxyB' len=4
5. 'A
B' len=5  <-- [separate line because CR/NL was correctly made part of s]
```
In cases 1, 2, and 3, the octal escapes embedded in the string literals assigned to the `string` variable `s` are not handled as expected, becoming character sequences starting with a backslash in `s`.  In case 1, `\0` becomes the four characters `\000`.  I believe `\0` should not appear in `s` at all since according to the spec, "\0 characters are ignored" when assigning to values of type `string`.  In cases 2 and 3, I believe `\015` and `\012` should become single bytes within `s` with decimal values 13 and 10.

Interestingly, cases 4 and 5 does work as expected.  The escapes are processed at some level, since `\170\171` becomes `xy` in case 4.  And case 5 shows that the escapes being part of a literal string matters, since using literal octal integers are fine.

